To align a row of divs to the right using flexbox in CSS, you can use the `justify-content` property and set it to `flex-end`. Here's an example:
```
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.item {
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  background-color: #eee;
  margin: 10px;
}
```
In this example, the `.container` element is set to `display: flex`, which enables flexbox layout. The `justify-content` property is then set to `flex-end`, which aligns the items in the container to the right. Finally, each item (`.item`) has a fixed width and height, as well as some margin for spacing.

You can also use other values for `justify-content` such as `center` or `space-between` to align the items differently.
